Prompting is a technique that is something that you gave as input text or instruction given to the language model to guide its output.
→prompt will be either questinoing , statement, or tasks, they are the use communicate their intent to the model.
A prompt is a message or instruction that tells an AI what task to perform.

Prompt techniques are strategies or methods used to design prompts in a way that helps AI models generate more accurate, relevant, and useful responses.
						Types of Prompts
1. Zero-Shot Prompting
2. One-Shot Prompting
3. Few-Shot Prompting
4. Instruction-Based Prompting
5. Role-Based Prompting
6. Chain-of-Thought (CoT) Prompting
7. Contextual Prompting
8. Iterative Prompting
 1. Zero-Shot Prompting: Zero-shot prompting involves giving the AI a task without providing any examples.

Example
Prompt:
	"Translate 'Good Morning' into French."
Output:
	"Bonjour"
	
	• Simple tasks 
	• Direct questions 
	• General knowledge queries 
Advantages:
	Ø Time saving
	Ø It is very useful for generates language day to day Activites, 
	Ø Simple and fast
	Ø Less token limit
	Ø Just need to give questinoing
Disadvantages:
	Ø No context (without examples it did not understand, it just generates answers
	Ø Less accuracy
	Ø If we want exact output than zero shot prompt will not work out
 
2.One shot prompting:  One-shot prompt is better than zero shot prompt it provide one single prompt to understand the model to generate the output.
Advantages
	Ø Helps the model understand the required format. 
	Ø Better accuracy than zero-shot prompting. 
	Ø Easy to implement. 
Disadvantages
	Ø Can lead to inconsistent outputs. 
	Ø Limited guidance for diverse scenarios. 
	Ø One example may not be sufficient for complex tasks. 

3.Few Shot prompting: Few shot prompting is better than zero and one shot prompt it provides some few examples to the model to generate the desired output.
→so it can recognize the pattern, soit will produce some accuracy output.
Advantages
	• Improves accuracy and consistency. 
	• Helps the model learn patterns. 
	• Effective for classification and extraction tasks. 
Disadvantages
	• Requires carefully selected examples. 
	• Longer prompts increase token usage. 
	• May not generalize well beyond provided examples.

4. Instruction-Based Prompting
Definition
Instruction-based prompting provides clear and explicit instructions about the task.
Example
Prompt: "Summarize the following article in 100 words."
Advantages
	• Easy to understand and use. 
	• Produces focused outputs. 
	• Works well for many NLP tasks. 
Disadvantages
	• Ambiguous instructions may cause errors. 
	• Output quality depends on instruction clarity. 
	• Complex tasks may need additional context. 

5. Role-Based Prompting
Definition
Role-based prompting assigns a specific role or personal to the AI before asking it to perform a task.
Example
Prompt: "Act as a software engineer and explain APIs."
Advantages
	• Generates domain-specific responses. 
	• Improves relevance and detail. 
	• Useful for simulations and expert advice. 
Disadvantages
	• AI may not always follow the role accurately. 
	• Can introduce bias based on the assigned role. 
	• Results depend on role description quality.

6. Chain-of-Thought (CoT) Prompting
Definition
Chain-of-Thought prompting encourages the model to reason through a problem step by step before providing an answer.
Example
Prompt: "Solve this math problem step by step."
Advantages
	• Improves reasoning and problem-solving. 
	• Helps with complex calculations. 
	• Makes the reasoning process transparent.
	• Better reasoning
	• Best for complex task. 
Disadvantages
	• Produces longer responses. 
	• Increases computation and token usage. 
	• Incorrect reasoning may still lead to wrong answers.
	• Slow response
	• Not needed for simple tasks

7. Contextual Prompting
Definition
Contextual prompting provides background information to help the model better understand the task.
Example
Prompt: "I am a beginner in Python. Explain loops with simple examples."
Advantages
	• Produces personalized responses. 
	• Improves relevance and accuracy. 
	• Helps the model understand user needs. 
Disadvantages
	• Requires additional context from the user. 
	• Long contexts increase prompt length. 
	• Irrelevant context may confuse the model.

8. Iterative Prompting
Definition
Iterative prompting involves refining prompts based on previous outputs to improve results.
Example
	1. "Write a paragraph about AI." 
	2. "Make it shorter." 
	3. "Add a real-world example." 
Advantages
	• Gradually improves output quality. 
	• Allows fine-tuning of responses. 
	• Useful for content creation and editing. 
Disadvantages
	• Requires multiple interactions. 
	• More time-consuming and costly.
	• May increase overall token usage.


	
	



